00:46:49.820 --> 00:46:52.110
to locate all these
downstream users,

00:46:52.110 --> 00:46:55.270
most of the problem is it's
the impossibility of it.

00:46:55.270 --> 00:46:56.570
They could be anywhere
in the world.

00:46:56.570 --> 00:46:57.730
How do you go after them?

00:46:57.730 --> 00:47:00.000
I think that's been
a lot of the problem

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:01.530
with anything that goes viral.

00:47:01.530 --> 00:47:05.230
I mean if you, you
know, take something

00:47:05.230 --> 00:47:06.930
so you've made another
copy rather

00:47:06.930 --> 00:47:09.620
than do what Getty Images
does and allow you to embed

00:47:09.620 --> 00:47:14.470
where you go back to the
source, it's really, you know,

00:47:14.470 --> 00:47:17.200
an impossibility to whether
it's under moral rights

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:19.690
or copyright infringement
really to enforce most

00:47:19.690 --> 00:47:21.300
of those downstream uses.

00:47:21.300 --> 00:47:24.090
&gt;&gt; Eugene Mopsik: And
I'll just say about if

00:47:24.090 --> 00:47:28.810
in fact the moral right is
waivable, I would venture

00:47:28.810 --> 00:47:32.640
to guess that when it
comes down to a negotiation

00:47:32.640 --> 00:47:34.550
with a photographer who's faced

00:47:34.550 --> 00:47:37.080
with what I call
the 30 day horizon

00:47:37.080 --> 00:47:41.130
which is the next billing cycle
and he's got to pay his bills

00:47:41.130 --> 00:47:43.530
and worried about rent
and everything else,

00:47:43.530 --> 00:47:47.340
he's going to give
up that right.

00:47:47.340 --> 00:47:48.570
No question.

00:47:48.570 --> 00:47:52.630
&gt;&gt; Sonya Bonneau: But if the law
gets too complicated then it can

00:47:52.630 --> 00:47:55.610
have the chilling
