then maybe the issue of all this
red flag knowledge would raise

00:49:31.920 --> 00:49:32.670
its head again.

00:49:32.670 --> 00:49:35.330
I mean if you knew what
was getting uploaded

00:49:35.330 --> 00:49:37.890
on your platform was
not by the same name

00:49:37.890 --> 00:49:39.810
as who was uploading it --

00:49:39.810 --> 00:49:41.130
&gt;&gt; Jane Ginsburg: It
would be interesting to --

00:49:41.130 --> 00:49:41.660
&gt;&gt; Nancy E. Wolf: Interesting.

00:49:41.660 --> 00:49:45.880
&gt;&gt; Jane Ginsburg: To construct
all of this, also I'll point

00:49:45.880 --> 00:49:50.820
out however that the,
at least under CMI,

00:49:50.820 --> 00:49:52.140
it's the rightsholder.

00:49:52.140 --> 00:49:55.790
And again the rightsholder is
not necessarily the author,

00:49:55.790 --> 00:50:00.240
so you would have to have a
basis for the author to protect

00:50:00.240 --> 00:50:02.290
that robust information.

00:50:02.290 --> 00:50:03.810
&gt;&gt; Eugene Mopsik: The
plus system does that.

00:50:03.810 --> 00:50:05.480
&gt;&gt; Nancy E. Wolf: Yeah,
the plus system is trying

00:50:05.480 --> 00:50:06.330
to do that right now.

00:50:06.330 --> 00:50:08.420
&gt;&gt; Eugene Mopsik: It recognizes
both the rights holder

00:50:08.420 --> 00:50:12.250
and the creator and
licensors, licensees.

00:50:12.250 --> 00:50:12.740
&gt;&gt; Jane Ginsburg: Right.

00:50:12.740 --> 00:50:13.990
But I mean in addition

00:50:13.990 --> 00:50:17.170
to the technical
basis, the legal basis.

00:50:17.170 --> 00:50:17.870
&gt;&gt; Eugene Mopsik: Right.

00:50:17.870 --> 00:50:18.630
&gt;&gt; Brad A. Greenberg:
Mickey, you've got the mic?

00:50:18.630 --> 00:50:19.260
&gt;&gt; Mickey Osterriecher: Yeah.

00:50:19.260 --> 00:50:21.820
Just we've been talking
about attribution rights

00:50:21.820 --> 00:50:25.090
versus economic rights but
